value.value: A transient developing limb structure that develops from the limb bud; it is a dorsoventral flattening of the limb bud structure and develops into the foot plate.
A membranous urethra of male or female that is part of a female urethra.

The shortest, least dilatable, and, with the exception of the external orifice, the narrowest part of the male urethral canal located in the deep perineal pouch and lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium; it extends downward and forward, with a slight anterior concavity, between the apex of the prostate and the bulb of the urethra, perforating the urogenital diaphragm below and behind the pubic symphysis; the membranous portion of the urethra is completely surrounded by the fibers of the sphincter urethrae membranaceae; on either side near its termination are the bulbourethral glands.

The slit-like opening of either ureter into the bladder; normally, the two ureteral orifices are placed at the posterolateral angles of the urinary bladder trigone while the internal urethral orifice is placed at its anteroinferior angle (apex); wide gaping usually indicates vesicoureteral reflux.
One of five swellings formed during the development of the face.
The point where the primary palate and both palatine shelves fuse.

The median slit located inferior and posterior to the external urethral orifice in the female; the exit for menstrual flow and birth and the entrance for the penis during sexual intercourse; the size and appearance of the vaginal orifice varies inversely with that of the hymen (G. membrane), a thin fold of mucous membrane that surrounds the vaginal orifice.
An artery of the neck.
The deep cervical artery (Profunda cervicalis) is an artery of the neck.
The transverse cervical artery (transverse artery of neck, transversa colli artery) is a branch of the thyrocervical trunk, running at a higher level than the suprascapular artery.
The caudal, swollen portion of the gubernaculum.
Keratinized stratified squamous epithelium is a stratified squamous epithelium, the cells of which synthesize and accumulate keratin.
The lymphocytic cell population present in the mucosa of the nasopharyngeal duct of some animals.
A broad fold of peritoneum that extends from the side of the uterus to the wall of the pelvis.
A pouch formed by the mesosalpinx and the mesovarium that encloses the infundibulum of the uterine tube and the ovary.

definition.value: Ovaries of some animals are surrounded by a thin membranous sac, the bursa, and are isolated from the peritoneal cavity. The bursa is continuous with the orifice of the oviduct. The bursa is not continuous in other mammals (eg., farm animals and human beings); ovaries of these species can be exposed within the abdomen, and thus ectopic pregnancy is possible[http://www.uwyo.edu/wjm/repro/femanat.htm]

value.value: A zone of skin that is part of the area surrounding the anus.

Any exocrine gland whose secretion consists of its own disintegrated secretory cells along with its secretory product; holocrine secretions are produced in the cytoplasm of the cell and released by the rupture of the plasma membrane, which destroys the cell and results in the secretion of the product into the lumen.
Pigmented, keratinised, hairless epidermis covering subcutaneous, collagenous, and adipose tissue.
A thick spongy structure at the base of the autopod, centred over the flexor surfaces of the distal interphalangeal joints.
An autopod pad found in the carpal region of a manus. Used for additional traction when stopping or descending a slope in digitigrade species.
An anatomical space that is enclosed by a urachus.
Extracellular matrix secreted by intraglomerular mesangial cells.
The segment of the autopod that is distal to the metapodial region and consists of the digits.
The segment of the manus that is distal to the metacarpal region and consists of the manual digits (fingers).
The segment of the pes that is distal to the metatarsal region and consists of the pedal digits (toes).
A bone that is part of a the digitopodium skeleton - i.e. the acropodial skeleton or the metapodial skeleton.
A bone that is part of a the manual digitopodium skeleton - i.e. the fingers or the metacarpal skeleton.
A bone that is part of a the pedal digitopodium skeleton - i.e. the toes or the metatarsal skeleton.
A bone element that is part of a jaw region.
An epithelium that is part of a thyroid follicle.
A muscle layer that is part of an intestine.

value.value: The inner layer of the muscular coat.

label.value: longitudinal muscle layer of muscular coat

value.value: The outer layer of the muscular coat.
A nerve plexus that is part of a sympathetic nervous system.
A layer of tissue between the muscularis and serosa.

definition.value: Contains nerves, blood vessels, lymphatics and lymph nodes

value.value: A muscular coat that is part of a jejunum.
A muscular coat that is part of a urinary bladder.

value.value: A circular muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a large intestine smooth muscle.

label.value: large intestine smooth muscle longitudinal layer

value.value: A longitudinal muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a large intestine smooth muscle.

value.value: A circular muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a small intestine smooth muscle.

label.value: small intestine smooth muscle longitudinal layer

value.value: A longitudinal muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a small intestine smooth muscle.
A smooth muscle tissue that is part of a respiratory system venous blood vessel.
A layer of microvilli, Thin cylindrical membrane-covered projections on the surface of an animal cell containing a core bundle of actin filaments[GO,modified].
A microvillus layer that is striated and found in the intestine.
Blood-forming tissue, consisting of reticular fibers and cells.

The sclera and cornea form the fibrous tunic of the bulb of the eye; the sclera is opaque, and constitutes the posterior five-sixths of the tunic; the cornea is transparent, and forms the anterior sixth.
